{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783912365236,"sessionID":"ses_0a68bc60effeJzWL51JC6bkniv","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_uEgabT2hdLRAOF8ZTPKv80dy","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/references/review_core.md","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/references/review_core.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Review Core Doctrine\n3: description: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"findings first severity ordering\"\n6:   - \"review finding schema\"\n7:   - \"severity contract for merge decisions\"\n8:   - \"evidence file line citation\"\n9:   - \"baseline surface precedence\"\n10:   - \"baseline check families\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.5.0.11\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # Review Core Doctrine\n17: \n18: Shared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## 2. SEVERITY DEFINITIONS\n29: \n30: | Level | Meaning | Handling |\n31: | --- | --- | --- |\n32: | P0 | Blocker: exploitable security issue, auth bypass, destructive data loss | Block merge |\n33: | P1 | Required: correctness bug, spec mismatch, must-fix gate issue | Fix before merge |\n34: | P2 | Suggestion: non-blocking improvement, documentation polish, style or maintainability follow-up | Optional or schedule follow-up |\n35: \n36: Escalation rule: if confidence is low but impact is high, classify toward the higher severity and state the uncertainty explicitly.\n37: \n38: ### Numeric Severity Calibration\n39: \n40: Numeric scores are advisory context, not the gate. A reviewer may add an optional `riskScore` to a finding and adjust it by `+/-2` for local context such as exploitability, blast radius, user impact, confidence, or proven containment. The merge/block decision remains the severity contract above: `P0` blocks, `P1` requires remediation, and `P2` is advisory. Do not adopt `score>=4` or any numeric threshold as a blocker.\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n45: \n46: - Every `P0` and `P1` finding must include a concrete `file:line` citation.\n47: - Evidence must tie the finding to observed code behavior, not just a general concern.\n48: - `P2` findings should still include specific evidence when available, even if impact is advisory.\n49: - If evidence is incomplete, state the assumption and why the risk still matters.\n50: \n51: ---\n52: \n53: ## 4. FINDINGS OUTPUT ORDERING\n54: \n55: - Present findings before summary or praise sections.\n56: - Order findings by severity first: `P0`, then `P1`, then `P2`.\n57: - Keep ordering stable within a severity bucket by impact and confidence.\n58: - Separate required fixes from optional suggestions so merge decisions stay clear.\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ## 5. BASELINE + SURFACE PRECEDENCE\n63: \n64: Apply this skill as the baseline first, then pair it with `sk-code` surface evidence when available:\n65: \n66: - Detected code surface -> `sk-code:<surface>`\n67: - Unclear surfaces -> baseline-only plus explicit uncertainty\n68: \n69: Precedence rules:\n70: \n71: - Baseline security and correctness minimums are always enforced.\n72: - Surface style, process, build, and test conventions override generic baseline guidance.\n73: - Unclear conflicts must be escalated rather than guessed.\n74: \n75: ---\n76: \n77: ## 6. BASELINE CHECK FAMILIES\n78: \n79: Mandatory baseline families:\n80: \n81: - Correctness minimums: regression risk, contract safety, spec mismatch, destructive side effects, and boundary handling.\n82: - Security minimums: auth and authorization gaps, injection exposure, unsafe secrets handling, privilege misuse, and reliability risks with security impact.\n83: \n84: These minimums cannot be relaxed by surface guidance.\n85: \n86: ---\n87: \n88: ## 7. FINDING SCHEMA\n89: \n90: Each finding should provide:\n91: \n92: | Field | Requirement |\n93: | --- | --- |\n94: | `id` | Stable label within the review report, such as `P1-001` |\n95: | `severity` | One of `P0`, `P1`, `P2` |\n96: | `title` | Short, risk-oriented summary |\n97: | `file` | Primary `path:line` location |\n98: | `evidence` | Plain-language explanation tied to observed code |\n99: | `findingClass` | One of `instance-only`, `class-of-bug`, `cross-consumer`, `algorithmic`, `matrix/evidence`, or `test-isolation` |\n100: | `scopeProof` | Grep/test/audit evidence that the recommendation covers same-class sites and consumers, or proves the finding is instance-only |\n101: | `affectedSurfaceHints` | Optional string array of producer/consumer surfaces the fix should address; recommended for actionable findings, required for cross-consumer findings. Use free-form short strings, max about 5 entries. Optional for instance-only findings. |\n102: | `riskScore` | Optional advisory number for relative risk calibration; never gating and never a substitute for `severity` |\n103: | `recommendation` | Specific, scope-proportional fix or follow-up |\n104: \n105: Suggested shape:\n106: \n107: ```markdown\n108: ### P1-001 [P1] Missing authorization check\n109: - File: path/to/file.ts:42\n110: - Evidence: Request handling reaches the write path before role validation.\n111: - Finding class: cross-consumer\n112: - Scope proof: `rg -n \"permission guard|write path\" path/to` shows the write handler is the only unchecked consumer.\n113: - Affected surface hints: [\"request handler\", \"write path\", \"permission guard\"]\n114: - riskScore: 6 (advisory only)\n115: - Recommendation: Enforce the existing permission guard before mutation.\n116: ```\n117: \n118: ---\n119: \n120: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n121: \n122: - [review_ux_single_pass.md](./review_ux_single_pass.md) - Interactive single-pass report flow and next-step prompts.\n123: - [quick_reference.md](./quick_reference.md) - Lightweight index across baseline review references.\n124: - [security_checklist.md](../assets/security_checklist.md) - Security and reliability checks.\n125: - [code_quality_checklist.md](../assets/code_quality_checklist.md) - Correctness, KISS, DRY, and maintainability checks.\n126: \n127: ---\n\n(End of file - total 127 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Review Core Doctrine\ndescription: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"findings first severity ordering\"\n  - \"review finding schema\"\n  - \"severity contract for merge decisions\"\n  - \"evidence file line citation\"\n  - \"baseline surface precedence\"\n  - \"baseline check families\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.5.0.11\n---\n\n# Review Core Doctrine\n\nShared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/references/review_core.md","text":"---\ntitle: Review Core Doctrine\ndescription: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"findings first severity ordering\"\n  - \"review finding schema\"\n  - \"severity contract for merge decisions\"\n  - \"evidence file line citation\"\n  - \"baseline surface precedence\"\n  - \"baseline check families\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.5.0.11\n---\n\n# Review Core Doctrine\n\nShared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nShared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SEVERITY DEFINITIONS\n\n| Level | Meaning | Handling |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| P0 | Blocker: exploitable security issue, auth bypass, destructive data loss | Block merge |\n| P1 | Required: correctness bug, spec mismatch, must-fix gate issue | Fix before merge |\n| P2 | Suggestion: non-blocking improvement, documentation polish, style or maintainability follow-up | Optional or schedule follow-up |\n\nEscalation rule: if confidence is low but impact is high, classify toward the higher severity and state the uncertainty explicitly.\n\n### Numeric Severity Calibration\n\nNumeric scores are advisory context, not the gate. A reviewer may add an optional `riskScore` to a finding and adjust it by `+/-2` for local context such as exploitability, blast radius, user impact, confidence, or proven containment. The merge/block decision remains the severity contract above: `P0` blocks, `P1` requires remediation, and `P2` is advisory. Do not adopt `score>=4` or any numeric threshold as a blocker.\n\n---\n\n## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Every `P0` and `P1` finding must include a concrete `file:line` citation.\n- Evidence must tie the finding to observed code behavior, not just a general concern.\n- `P2` findings should still include specific evidence when available, even if impact is advisory.\n- If evidence is incomplete, state the assumption and why the risk still matters.\n\n---\n\n## 4. FINDINGS OUTPUT ORDERING\n\n- Present findings before summary or praise sections.\n- Order findings by severity first: `P0`, then `P1`, then `P2`.\n- Keep ordering stable within a severity bucket by impact and confidence.\n- Separate required fixes from optional suggestions so merge decisions stay clear.\n\n---\n\n## 5. BASELINE + SURFACE PRECEDENCE\n\nApply this skill as the baseline first, then pair it with `sk-code` surface evidence when available:\n\n- Detected code surface -> `sk-code:<surface>`\n- Unclear surfaces -> baseline-only plus explicit uncertainty\n\nPrecedence rules:\n\n- Baseline security and correctness minimums are always enforced.\n- Surface style, process, build, and test conventions override generic baseline guidance.\n- Unclear conflicts must be escalated rather than guessed.\n\n---\n\n## 6. BASELINE CHECK FAMILIES\n\nMandatory baseline families:\n\n- Correctness minimums: regression risk, contract safety, spec mismatch, destructive side effects, and boundary handling.\n- Security minimums: auth and authorization gaps, injection exposure, unsafe secrets handling, privilege misuse, and reliability risks with security impact.\n\nThese minimums cannot be relaxed by surface guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 7. FINDING SCHEMA\n\nEach finding should provide:\n\n| Field | Requirement |\n| --- | --- |\n| `id` | Stable label within the review report, such as `P1-001` |\n| `severity` | One of `P0`, `P1`, `P2` |\n| `title` | Short, risk-oriented summary |\n| `file` | Primary `path:line` location |\n| `evidence` | Plain-language explanation tied to observed code |\n| `findingClass` | One of `instance-only`, `class-of-bug`, `cross-consumer`, `algorithmic`, `matrix/evidence`, or `test-isolation` |\n| `scopeProof` | Grep/test/audit evidence that the recommendation covers same-class sites and consumers, or proves the finding is instance-only |\n| `affectedSurfaceHints` | Optional string array of producer/consumer surfaces the fix should address; recommended for actionable findings, required for cross-consumer findings. Use free-form short strings, max about 5 entries. Optional for instance-only findings. |\n| `riskScore` | Optional advisory number for relative risk calibration; never gating and never a substitute for `severity` |\n| `recommendation` | Specific, scope-proportional fix or follow-up |\n\nSuggested shape:\n\n```markdown\n### P1-001 [P1] Missing authorization check\n- File: path/to/file.ts:42\n- Evidence: Request handling reaches the write path before role validation.\n- Finding class: cross-consumer\n- Scope proof: `rg -n \"permission guard|write path\" path/to` shows the write handler is the only unchecked consumer.\n- Affected surface hints: [\"request handler\", \"write path\", \"permission guard\"]\n- riskScore: 6 (advisory only)\n- Recommendation: Enforce the existing permission guard before mutation.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [review_ux_single_pass.md](./review_ux_single_pass.md) - Interactive single-pass report flow and next-step prompts.\n- [quick_reference.md](./quick_reference.md) - Lightweight index across baseline review references.\n- [security_checklist.md](../assets/security_checklist.md) - Security and reliability checks.\n- [code_quality_checklist.md](../assets/code_quality_checklist.md) - Correctness, KISS, DRY, and maintainability checks.\n\n---","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":127,"totalLines":127,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/references/review_core.md","time":{"start":1783912365230,"end":1783912365235}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03cf31c0fddf401c016a5457acf4e48191a6cc74a1f99e79f6"}},"id":"prt_f59767cad001VXrYUulYw3jjZF","sessionID":"ses_0a68bc60effeJzWL51JC6bkniv","messageID":"msg_f59763270001g4GLbV5e1ms3KF"}}
