{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783912491647,"sessionID":"ses_0a68bc60effeJzWL51JC6bkniv","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_thQxjF110lSuNCJE0hjrjiP2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Reference File Templates\n3: description: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill reference templates\"\n6:   - \"reference file structure\"\n7:   - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n8:   - \"reference creation guidelines\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.8.0.16\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n15: \n16: Templates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Location & Naming\n23: \n24: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n25: \n26: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n27: \n28: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n29: |---------------|-----------------|\n30: | `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n31: | `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n32: | `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n33: | `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n34: | `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n35: \n36: ### When to Create References\n37: \n38: **Create a reference file when:**\n39: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n40: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n41: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n42: - Systematic debugging procedures\n43: - Tool integration details\n44: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n45: \n46: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n47: - Content under 200 lines\n48: - Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n49: - Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n50: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n55: \n56: ### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n57: \n58: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n59: \n60: ```markdown\n61: ---\n62: title: [Title]\n63: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n64: trigger_phrases:\n65:   - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n66:   - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n67:   - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\n68: importance_tier: normal\n69: contextType: general\n70: version: 1.0.0.0\n71: ---\n72: \n73: # [Title]\n74: \n75: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n80: [All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n81: \n82: ```\n83: \n84: Every reference file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`, `important` only for formal contract docs; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n85: \n86: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n87: > The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n88: \n89: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n90: \n91: ```markdown\n92: # Git Commit Workflows\n93: \n94: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n95: \n96: ---\n97: \n98: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n99: \n100: ### Purpose\n101: Provides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n102: \n103: ### When to Use\n104: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n105: - Filtering generated files from commits\n106: - Writing clear commit messages\n107: \n108: ### Core Principle\n109: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n110: ```\n111: \n112: #### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n113: \n114: ```markdown\n115: # Git Commit Workflows\n116: \n117: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n118: \n119: ### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n120: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n121: \n122: ### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n123: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n124: \n125: ---\n126: \n127: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n128: \n129: ### Purpose\n130: Provides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n131: \n132: ### Core Principle\n133: Atomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n134: ```\n135: \n136: #### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n137: \n138: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n139: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n140: | 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n141: | Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n142: | When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n143: | Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n144: | Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n145: | Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n146: | Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n151: \n152: Reference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n153: \n154: **Core Purpose**:\n155: - **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n156: - **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n157: - **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n158: - **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n159: - **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n160: \n161: **Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n162: - AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n163: - Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n164: \n165: ### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n166: \n167: ```\n168: Level 1: Metadata (name + description)\n169:          └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n170:             ↓\n171: Level 2: SKILL.md body\n172:          └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n173:             ↓\n174: Level 3: Reference files (this document)\n175:          └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n176: ```\n177: \n178: **Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n179: \n180: ---\n181: \n182: ## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n183: \n184: ### Create Reference File When\n185: \n186: **Workflow Complexity**:\n187: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n188: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n189: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n190: - Systematic debugging procedures\n191: \n192: **Technical Depth**:\n193: - Root cause analysis required\n194: - Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n195: - Before/after code transformations\n196: - Common error patterns and fixes\n197: \n198: **Size Threshold**:\n199: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n200: - Multiple related workflows\n201: - Extensive troubleshooting needed\n202: \n203: ### Keep in SKILL.md When\n204: \n205: **Core Content**:\n206: - Overview and \"When to Use\"\n207: - High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n208: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n209:   > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n210: - Quick reference\n211: \n212: **Size**: Content under 200 lines\n213: \n214: ### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n215: \n216: | Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n217: | ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n218: | **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n219: | **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n220: | **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |\n221: | **Debugging**       | Systematic troubleshooting             | `debugging_workflows.md`      | 600-1200 lines |\n222: | **Tool Guide**      | MCP/external tool integration          | `devtools_guide.md`           | 200-600 lines  |\n223: | **Quick Reference** | Commands, shortcuts, checklists        | `quick_reference.md`          | 200-400 lines  |\n224: \n225: **Note:** All reference file names use snake_case (underscores, lowercase).\n226: \n227: ---\n228: \n229: ## 4. AI AGENT SKILL REFERENCE CHARACTERISTICS\n230: \n231: ### Core Principle Statements\n232: \n233: **Purpose**: Distill philosophy into one-line wisdom\n234: \n235: > **PLACEMENT**: Core Principle goes in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph after the H1 title.\n236: \n237: **Format**:\n238: ```markdown\n239: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n240: \n241: ### Core Principle\n242: \n243: [Single powerful statement that captures the workflow's essence]\n244: ```\n245: \n246: **Examples from Real Skills**:\n247: - \"Wait for the actual condition you care about, not a guess about how long it takes\"\n248: - \"ALWAYS find root cause before attempting fixes. Symptom fixes are failure\"\n249: - \"Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history\"\n250: \n251: ### Phased Workflows with Validation\n252: \n253: **Purpose**: Structured processes with mandatory checkpoints\n254: \n255: **Format**:\n256: ```markdown\n257: ### The [Number] Phases\n258: \n259: You MUST complete each phase before proceeding to the next.\n260: \n261: #### Phase 1: [Phase Name]\n262: \n263: **Purpose**: [What this phase accomplishes]\n264: \n265: **Actions**:\n266: 1. [Action 1]\n267: 2. [Action 2]\n268: \n269: **Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n270: \n271: #### Phase 2: [Phase Name]\n272: \n273: [Similar structure]\n274: ```\n275: \n276: **Key Elements**:\n277: - **\"You MUST complete\"** - Mandatory language\n278: - **Named checkpoints** - `checkpoint_name` for validation\n279: - **Sequential phases** - Cannot skip ahead\n280: \n281: ### Before/After Code Examples\n282: \n283: **Purpose**: Show transformation from wrong to right\n284: \n285: **Format**:\n286: ```markdown\n287: ### [Pattern Name]\n288: \n289: **BEFORE**: [Problem description]\n290: \\```[language]\n291: // Bad code with issues\n292: // Showing what NOT to do\n293: \\```\n294: \n295: **AFTER**: [Solution description]\n296: \\```[language]\n297: // Good code with fixes\n298: // Showing correct approach\n299: \\```\n300: \n301: **Why better**: [Explanation of improvement]\n302: ```\n303: \n304: **Key Elements**:\n305: - `BEFORE:` marker for the wrong-way code\n306: - `AFTER:` marker for the right-way code\n307: - Inline comments explaining issues\n308: - \"Why better\" rationale\n309: \n310: ### Pattern Comparison Tables\n311: \n312: **Purpose**: Compare approaches across scenarios\n313: \n314: **Format**:\n315: ```markdown\n316: ### Common Patterns\n317: \n318: | Scenario     | Approach A (Wrong) | Approach B (Right) | Why Better  |\n319: | ------------ | ------------------ | ------------------ | ----------- |\n320: | [Scenario 1] | [Wrong way]        | [Right way]        | [Rationale] |\n321: | [Scenario 2] | [Wrong way]        | [Right way]        | [Rationale] |\n322: ```\n323: \n324: **Use when**: Multiple scenarios need comparison\n325: \n326: ### Decision Logic in Markdown\n327: \n328: **Purpose**: Explicit if/then logic for workflow decisions\n329: \n330: **Format**:\n331: \\```markdown\n332: ### Decision Logic\n333: \n334: \\```markdown\n335: IF [condition A]:\n336:   → [Action/Path A]\n337:   → [Expected outcome A]\n338: \n339: IF [condition B]:\n340:   → [Action/Path B]\n341:   → [Expected outcome B]\n342: \n343: IF [condition C]:\n344:   → [Action/Path C]\n345:   → [Expected outcome C]\n346: \\```\n347: \\```\n348: \n349: **Alternative format** (decision tree):\n350: \\```markdown\n351: \\```\n352: Analyze situation\n353: ├─ Condition A met\n354: │  └─ Execute Workflow A\n355: │     └─ Expected outcome A\n356: ├─ Condition B met\n357: │  └─ Execute Workflow B\n358: │     └─ Expected outcome B\n359: └─ Condition C met\n360:    └─ Execute Workflow C\n361:       └─ Expected outcome C\n362: \\```\n363: \\```\n364: \n365: ### Validation Checkpoints\n366: \n367: **Purpose**: Named checkpoints throughout workflows\n368: \n369: **Format**:\n370: ```markdown\n371: **Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n372: ```\n373: \n374: **Examples**:\n375: - `files_analyzed`\n376: - `artifacts_filtered`\n377: - `strategy_determined`\n378: - `root_cause_identified`\n379: \n380: **Usage**: Reference in quality checklists and debugging\n381: \n382: ### Prerequisites Section\n383: \n384: **Purpose**: Link to required standards and context\n385: \n386: > **PLACEMENT**: Prerequisites go in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph.\n387: \n388: **Format**:\n389: ```markdown\n390: # [Workflow Name]\n391: \n392: [1-2 sentence summary only - no prerequisites here]\n393: \n394: ---\n395: \n396: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n397: \n398: ### Prerequisites\n399: Follow [standard name] for all implementations:\n400: - **[Standard 1]**: [Brief description]\n\n(Showing lines 1-400 of 1025. Use offset=401 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill reference templates\"\n  - \"reference file structure\"\n  - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n  - \"reference creation guidelines\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.16\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill reference templates\"\n  - \"reference file structure\"\n  - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n  - \"reference creation guidelines\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.16\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n| `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n| `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n| `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n| `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n\n### When to Create References\n\n**Create a reference file when:**\n- Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n- Decision trees with multiple branches\n- Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n- Systematic debugging procedures\n- Tool integration details\n- Content exceeds 200 lines\n\n**Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n- Content under 200 lines\n- Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n- Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n- Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n\n---\n\n## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n\n### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n\n**CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: [Title]\ndescription: [One-line description - same as intro]\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# [Title]\n\n[1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n[All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n\n```\n\nEvery reference file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`, `important` only for formal contract docs; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n\n> **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n> The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n\n#### GOOD Intro Structure\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Workflows\n\nStep-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProvides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n\n### When to Use\n- Creating commits with multiple file changes\n- Filtering generated files from commits\n- Writing clear commit messages\n\n### Core Principle\nAtomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n```\n\n#### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Workflows\n\nStep-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n\n### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\nAtomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n\n### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n- Creating commits with multiple file changes\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProvides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n\n### Core Principle\nAtomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n```\n\n#### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n\n| Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n| --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n| 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n| Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n| Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n\n---\n\n### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n\nReference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n\n**Core Purpose**:\n- **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n- **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n- **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n- **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n- **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n\n**Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n- AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n- Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n\n### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n\n```\nLevel 1: Metadata (name + description)\n         └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n            ↓\nLevel 2: SKILL.md body\n         └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n            ↓\nLevel 3: Reference files (this document)\n         └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n```\n\n**Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n\n---\n\n## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n\n### Create Reference File When\n\n**Workflow Complexity**:\n- Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n- Decision trees with multiple branches\n- Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n- Systematic debugging procedures\n\n**Technical Depth**:\n- Root cause analysis required\n- Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n- Before/after code transformations\n- Common error patterns and fixes\n\n**Size Threshold**:\n- Content exceeds 200 lines\n- Multiple related workflows\n- Extensive troubleshooting needed\n\n### Keep in SKILL.md When\n\n**Core Content**:\n- Overview and \"When to Use\"\n- High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n- Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n  > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n- Quick reference\n\n**Size**: Content under 200 lines\n\n### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n\n| Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n| ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n| **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n| **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n| **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |\n| **Debugging**       | Systematic troubleshooting             | `debugging_workflows.md`      | 600-1200 lines |\n| **Tool Guide**      | MCP/external tool integration          | `devtools_guide.md`           | 200-600 lines  |\n| **Quick Reference** | Commands, shortcuts, checklists        | `quick_reference.md`          | 200-400 lines  |\n\n**Note:** All reference file names use snake_case (underscores, lowercase).\n\n---\n\n## 4. AI AGENT SKILL REFERENCE CHARACTERISTICS\n\n### Core Principle Statements\n\n**Purpose**: Distill philosophy into one-line wisdom\n\n> **PLACEMENT**: Core Principle goes in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph after the H1 title.\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\n[Single powerful statement that captures the workflow's essence]\n```\n\n**Examples from Real Skills**:\n- \"Wait for the actual condition you care about, not a guess about how long it takes\"\n- \"ALWAYS find root cause before attempting fixes. Symptom fixes are failure\"\n- \"Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history\"\n\n### Phased Workflows with Validation\n\n**Purpose**: Structured processes with mandatory checkpoints\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n### The [Number] Phases\n\nYou MUST complete each phase before proceeding to the next.\n\n#### Phase 1: [Phase Name]\n\n**Purpose**: [What this phase accomplishes]\n\n**Actions**:\n1. [Action 1]\n2. [Action 2]\n\n**Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n\n#### Phase 2: [Phase Name]\n\n[Similar structure]\n```\n\n**Key Elements**:\n- **\"You MUST complete\"** - Mandatory language\n- **Named checkpoints** - `checkpoint_name` for validation\n- **Sequential phases** - Cannot skip ahead\n\n### Before/After Code Examples\n\n**Purpose**: Show transformation from wrong to right\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n### [Pattern Name]\n\n**BEFORE**: [Problem description]\n\\```[language]\n// Bad code with issues\n// Showing what NOT to do\n\\```\n\n**AFTER**: [Solution description]\n\\```[language]\n// Good code with fixes\n// Showing correct approach\n\\```\n\n**Why better**: [Explanation of improvement]\n```\n\n**Key Elements**:\n- `BEFORE:` marker for the wrong-way code\n- `AFTER:` marker for the right-way code\n- Inline comments explaining issues\n- \"Why better\" rationale\n\n### Pattern Comparison Tables\n\n**Purpose**: Compare approaches across scenarios\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n### Common Patterns\n\n| Scenario     | Approach A (Wrong) | Approach B (Right) | Why Better  |\n| ------------ | ------------------ | ------------------ | ----------- |\n| [Scenario 1] | [Wrong way]        | [Right way]        | [Rationale] |\n| [Scenario 2] | [Wrong way]        | [Right way]        | [Rationale] |\n```\n\n**Use when**: Multiple scenarios need comparison\n\n### Decision Logic in Markdown\n\n**Purpose**: Explicit if/then logic for workflow decisions\n\n**Format**:\n\\```markdown\n### Decision Logic\n\n\\```markdown\nIF [condition A]:\n  → [Action/Path A]\n  → [Expected outcome A]\n\nIF [condition B]:\n  → [Action/Path B]\n  → [Expected outcome B]\n\nIF [condition C]:\n  → [Action/Path C]\n  → [Expected outcome C]\n\\```\n\\```\n\n**Alternative format** (decision tree):\n\\```markdown\n\\```\nAnalyze situation\n├─ Condition A met\n│  └─ Execute Workflow A\n│     └─ Expected outcome A\n├─ Condition B met\n│  └─ Execute Workflow B\n│     └─ Expected outcome B\n└─ Condition C met\n   └─ Execute Workflow C\n      └─ Expected outcome C\n\\```\n\\```\n\n### Validation Checkpoints\n\n**Purpose**: Named checkpoints throughout workflows\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n**Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n```\n\n**Examples**:\n- `files_analyzed`\n- `artifacts_filtered`\n- `strategy_determined`\n- `root_cause_identified`\n\n**Usage**: Reference in quality checklists and debugging\n\n### Prerequisites Section\n\n**Purpose**: Link to required standards and context\n\n> **PLACEMENT**: Prerequisites go in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph.\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n# [Workflow Name]\n\n[1-2 sentence summary only - no prerequisites here]\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Prerequisites\nFollow [standard name] for all implementations:\n- **[Standard 1]**: [Brief description]","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":400,"totalLines":1025,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","time":{"start":1783912491641,"end":1783912491646}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08a3a0123d962a1f016a54582b88c8819180c0e248bce673b8"}},"id":"prt_f59786a700019Wv0BJN2dVIT5G","sessionID":"ses_0a68bc60effeJzWL51JC6bkniv","messageID":"msg_f59781162001tIgBoH4FooIbhj"}}
